    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-04-14T17:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-04-14T04:30:00-05:00" n="119"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d119">
                <head>119. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d119fn1"
                        >Source: Ford Library, National Security Adviser, Memoranda of
                        Conversations, Box 19, April 14, 1976—<persName corresp="#p_FGR_1"
                            >Ford</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Scowcroft</persName>,
                        Senator <persName corresp="#p_JJK_1">Jacob Javits</persName>. Confidential.
                        The meeting was held in the White House Oval Office.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1976-04-14T04:30:00-05:00" to="1976-04-14T17:10:00-05:00">April
                            14, 1976, 4:30–5:10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Senator <persName corresp="#p_JJK_1">Jacob Javits</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Brent Scowcroft</persName>, Assistant to the
                        President for National Security Affairs</item>
                    <item>Max Friedersdorf, Assistant to the President</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_JJK_1">Javits</persName>: I am ready to help your campaign
                    whenever you push the button.</p>
                <p>President: We had two good days in Texas. We had a little flap over Panama.
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDJ_1">Dan Flood</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_SME_1">Snyder</persName> —<persName corresp="#p_RRW_1"
                        >Reagan</persName> picked that up.<note n="2" xml:id="d119fn2">President
                            <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName> was campaigning in Texas
                        ahead of that state’s May primary, and he faced a barrage of criticism from
                            <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> supporters on a variety
                        of issues, including Panama. (“<persName corresp="#p_RRW_1"
                            >Reagan</persName>’s Issues Pursue <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1"
                            >Ford</persName> in Texas,” <hi rend="italic">The New York Times</hi>,
                        April 11, 1976, p. 40)</note> It’s sheer demagogery.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_JJK_1">Javits</persName>: May I make a suggestion? I met
                    with <persName corresp="#p_THOE_1">Torrijos</persName> at the State Department’s
                        suggestion.<note n="3" xml:id="d119fn3">See <ref target="#d110fn2">footnote
                            2, Document 110</ref>.</note> I think you should be very presidential
                    about this. This is an important issue for the U.S., Panama, and Latin
                    America.</p>
                <p>President: I thought I would lay the whole thing out. It is based on a purchase
                    we made in 1903. In no circumstances will we go beyond the seven principles [of
                    February 1974].<note n="4" xml:id="d119fn4">Brackets in the original.</note> The
                    reason we started negotiations in 1964 was we had riots in which both Americans
                    and Panamanians were killed. Wave a paper on the riots and say we are
                    negotiating to avoid a repetition of that. We also want to avoid losing all of
                    Latin America, including Mexico with whom we have 6,000 miles of border.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_JJK_1">Javits</persName>: I only have one suggestion.
                    Instead of saying first that we will lose our friends, say first the importance
                    is placed on this treaty—then say we will lose all our friends.</p>
                <p>President: I think we should take the offensive on this.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_JJK_1">Javits</persName>: I agree. Be the President.</p>
                <p>[<hi rend="roman">Omitted here is discussion of the Middle East.]</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
